  # Global rules (VERY STRICT)
  Rule: Respect existing working structure
    - Do not change any HTML structure, IDs, classes, or JS logic
    - Do not rename existing i18n keys that are already used in HTML/JS
    - Only:
      - Fix text values
      - Add missing keys
      - Remove clearly unused/duplicate keys
    - Keep code style, formatting, and indentation consistent with existing files

  Rule: Encoding and strange characters
    - All files must be treated as UTF-8 (no BOM if possible)
    - Detect and fix all strange characters such as:
      - Replacement characters (�)
      - Sequences of question marks instead of proper letters (e.g. "????")
      - Broken diacritics or punctuation
    - Preserve correct Dutch characters (é, è, ë, ï, 's, etc.) and English punctuation
    - After fixing, the text must be human-readable, natural, and clean

  Rule: Language quality
    - Dutch (nl) must follow natural, modern INTEC website style
    - English (en) must be clear, professional, and natural for an educational website
    - Avoid literal machine translation if it sounds weird
    - Fix obvious grammar, spelling, and capitalization issues in both languages

  Scenario: Build a complete translation inventory
    Given you load en.js and nl.js as key-value dictionaries
    And you parse all the HTML pages listed above
    When you scan for:
      - data-i18n or similar attributes
      - any JS usages of i18n keys
      - hard-coded visible text in Dutch or English inside HTML
    Then you must:
      - Produce an internal mapping of:
        - key -> nl value
        - key -> en value
        - where it is used (file + approx location)
      - Detect:
        - keys used in HTML but missing in en.js or nl.js
        - keys defined in en.js/nl.js but never used anywhere
        - keys where nl and en texts clearly do not match in meaning

  Scenario: Fix missing and inconsistent translations
    Given the mapping of keys and usages
    When a key is used in HTML but:
      - Missing in nl.js or en.js
      Or the translation is clearly wrong or incomplete
    Then:
      - Treat Dutch as the primary source when Dutch text exists
      - Generate a high-quality English translation for the corresponding key
      - When only English exists, generate a natural Dutch translation
      - Ensure both nl and en values express the same meaning and tone
      - Add the missing keys to en.js and/or nl.js in the correct section
      - Avoid duplicates: reuse existing keys when meaning is identical

  Scenario: Remove dead or duplicate keys safely
    Given the list of all keys that are not referenced in any HTML or JS
    When a key is clearly unused
    Then:
      - Mark it as a dead key
      - Remove it from en.js and nl.js
      - But only if you are sure it is not part of a pattern or future use
    And when two or more keys contain identical or near-identical text:
      - Prefer one canonical key
      - Keep the others only if they serve a clearly different context
      - Do NOT perform aggressive merging that could break context

  Scenario: Normalize and repair weird symbols
    Given all translation values in en.js and nl.js
    When you detect:
      - Garbled sequences
      - Question marks or replacement characters inside words
      - HTML entities that are broken or unnecessary
    Then:
      - Replace them with the correct characters
      - Ensure quotes and apostrophes are consistent (e.g. use ’ or ' but not mixed randomly)
      - Ensure there are no unintended double spaces or broken line breaks

  Scenario: Synchronize HTML with i18n system
    Given the cleaned and updated en.js and nl.js
    When you review each of the HTML files
    Then:
      - Ensure all visible textual content that should be translatable is backed by i18n keys
      - Replace remaining hard-coded Dutch/English text with i18n usage where appropriate
      - Do NOT change layout, components, or JavaScript behavior
      - Keep accessibility attributes (aria-label, title, alt) meaningful and correctly translated

  Scenario: Final consistency and integrity check
    Given all changes to en.js, nl.js, and the HTML files
    When you perform a final validation
    Then:
      - Ensure there are no missing keys at runtime (no undefined translation lookups)
      - Ensure both languages load without JS errors
      - Ensure no strange characters remain visible on any page
      - Summarize in a short report (in comments or separate text) the changes:
        - Number of keys added, updated, removed
        - Main categories of fixes (missing translations, encoding, wording)
      - Confirm that you respected the "do not break working structure" rule

  # Style & discipline
  Rule: Work as a strict professional
    - Be conservative: prefer safe fixes over risky refactors
    - Be explicit and deterministic in how you map texts to keys
    - Never introduce experimental features or redesign UI in this task
    - Focus 100% on translation consistency, data cleanliness, and encoding correctness
